Collider and things

00:42:43.520 --> 00:42:48.950
like that-- they are a lot
more difficult to recreate.

00:42:48.950 --> 00:42:51.553
I think today,
education policy is

00:42:51.553 --> 00:42:57.370
sort of pushing kids
into much more sort

00:42:57.370 --> 00:42:59.530
of systematic ways of learning.

00:42:59.530 --> 00:43:01.030
You're less encouraged
to run around

00:43:01.030 --> 00:43:04.550
ponds gathering up slime and
seeing what happens with it.

00:43:04.550 --> 00:43:08.090
Or those chemistry sets we
used to have as kids-- really

00:43:08.090 --> 00:43:09.700
dangerous things in them.

00:43:09.700 --> 00:43:12.419
I think they're a lot more
closely regulated nowadays.

00:43:12.419 --> 00:43:14.210
But certainly,
Enlightenment culture really

00:43:14.210 --> 00:43:16.590
encouraged people
to question things,

00:43:16.590 --> 00:43:19.400
to try things out
for themselves.

00:43:19.400 --> 00:43:24.130
And a lot of the people
I've spoken about today

00:43:24.130 --> 00:43:25.320
are quite elite scientists.

00:43:25.320 --> 00:43:26.986
A lot of them were
members of academies,

00:43:26.986 --> 00:43:29.059
like the World Society
in London or Paris.

00:43:29.059 --> 00:43:31.600
But actually, there were huge
numbers of working-class people

00:43:31.600 --> 00:43:33.440
involved in this kind of thing.

00:43:33.440 --> 00:43:36.715
There were a lot of working
men forming botanical clubs.

00:43:36.715 --> 00:43:39.340
There were zoological clubs, who
would put their money together

00:43:39.340 --> 00:43:41.990
and buy a library for
themselves and keep in the pub

00:43:41.990 --> 00:43:43.740
or something like that.

00:43:43.740 --> 00:43:46.620
So all across society, a
lot of people were, I think,

00:43:46.620 --> 00:43:49.570
much more interested in
science and basic science

00:43:49.570 --> 00:43:51.300
than they are today.

00:43:51.300 --> 00:43:54.411
Thank you for the question.

