00:44:52.554 --> 00:44:55.922
MALE SPEAKER: There's
a question here.

00:44:55.922 --> 00:44:59.260
AUDIENCE: Is a piece of coral
considered an animal, or just

00:44:59.260 --> 00:45:01.240
an individual polyp?

00:45:01.240 --> 00:45:03.690
SUSANNAH GIBSON:
That's a good question.

00:45:03.690 --> 00:45:04.760
I'll repeat the question.

00:45:04.760 --> 00:45:08.680
The question was, is a coral
considered an animal or just

00:45:08.680 --> 00:45:09.910
a polyp?

00:45:09.910 --> 00:45:14.330
So they're kind of
a colony of animals.

00:45:14.330 --> 00:45:18.400
So within one coral, you'll have
thousands of individual polyps.

00:45:18.400 --> 00:45:20.730
Each policy secretes-- they
kind of act like a snail.

00:45:20.730 --> 00:45:22.832
They make a hard shell
around themselves,

00:45:22.832 --> 00:45:25.040
and when you join thousands
of these things together,

00:45:25.040 --> 00:45:27.230
they form what looks
like a coral to us.

00:45:30.860 --> 00:45:32.680
So it's quite a
difficult question

00:45:32.680 --> 00:45:35.182
to answer, because
in a way a coral does

00:45:35.182 --> 00:45:37.390
act a bit like a plant,
because the colony of animals

00:45:37.390 --> 00:45:39.410
all joins together and
support each other.

00:45:39.410 --> 00:45:41.502
And if you just had
one living on its own,

00:45:41.502 --> 00:45:45.310
it probably wouldn't
fare that well.

00:45:45.310 --> 00:45:47.780
And also, to just get
back to my disclaimer,

00:45:47.780 --> 00:45:50.210
I'm not a scientist.

00:45:50.210 --> 00:45:51.640
But it's a good question.

00:45:51.640 --> 00:45:54.400
Does anyone else know
the answer to that?

00:45:54.400 --> 00:45:57.214
AUDIENCE: [INAUDIBLE] similar
