00:46:24.425 --> 00:46:26.230
they brought [INAUDIBLE].

00:46:26.230 --> 00:46:28.765
Is there an acknowledgement
within the science community,

00:46:28.765 --> 00:46:31.700
we'll call it the history
of science, as to what

00:46:31.700 --> 00:46:33.965
people [INAUDIBLE] personally
and how that influences

00:46:33.965 --> 00:46:39.125
their results, and how to
get over that or around that?

00:46:39.125 --> 00:46:40.500
SUSANNAH GIBSON:
That probably is

00:46:40.500 --> 00:46:43.557
one of the biggest topics that
comes up in history of science

00:46:43.557 --> 00:46:44.390
over and over again.

00:46:44.390 --> 00:46:47.620
And the fact is, because
science is a human activity,

00:46:47.620 --> 00:46:49.510
it's kind of inherently flawed.

00:46:49.510 --> 00:46:51.460
And everyone comes to
science with an agenda.

00:46:51.460 --> 00:46:53.760
And there is the
idea that there is

00:46:53.760 --> 00:46:55.260
such thing as the
scientific method

00:46:55.260 --> 00:46:57.460
and it's completely impartial.

00:46:57.460 --> 00:47:00.527
And on paper it is,
but in reality, science

00:47:00.527 --> 00:47:02.110
is being done with
people, and they're

00:47:02.110 --> 00:47:06.130
being funded by people who want
particular things from them.

00:47:06.130 --> 00:47:11.780
I know someone who is working
for a large and unnamed tobacco

00:47:11.780 --> 00:47:13.800
company, working
out whether or not

00:47:13.800 --> 00:47:17.830
tobacco plants have certain
concentrations of carcinogenic

00:47:17.830 --> 00:47:19.070
chemicals in them.

00:47:19.070 --> 00:47:20.940
But her research is
being funded by someone

00:47:20.940 --> 00:47:22.600
who wants a particular answer.

00:47:22.600 --> 00:47:25.200
And that's kind of an
extreme example of that case,

00:47:25.200 --> 00:47:28.180
but even in the
most impartial lab,

00:47:28.180 --> 00:47:30.000
people often approach
an experiment

00:47:30.000 --> 00:47:31.820
with the result in mind.

00:47:31.820 --> 00:47:33.770
People often start off
an experiment thinking,

00:47:33.770 --> 00:47:36.247
oh, I think it's
probably a 90% chance

00:47:36.247 --> 00:47:37.330
that it will lead to this.

00:47:37.330 --> 00:47:39.362
And often, if that result
doesn't come about,

00:47:39.362 --> 00:47:41.070
people just try it
over and over and over

00:47:41.070 --> 00:47:44.100
until-- it takes an
awfully long time,

00:47:44.100 --> 00:47:46.390
I think, for people to give
up their preconceptions.

00:47:46.390 --> 00:47:47.322
when

00:47:47.322 --> 00:47:49.530
I started off as a scientist
but now I'm a historian,

00:47:49.530 --> 00:47:51.960
and it gives you such a
different view science,

00:47:51.960 --> 00:47:54.060
seeing how, through
the last 2,000 years,

00:47:54.060 --> 00:47:58.510
people have shaped their
answers to what society wanted

00:47:58.510 --> 00:48:00.010
from them and to
their own religious

00:48:00.010 --> 00:48:04.120
and social and
philosophical beliefs.

00:48:04.120 --> 00:48:07.320
I think it would be quite
hard as a working scientist.

00:48:07.320 --> 00:48:10.280
I think you have to be a
realist as a working scientist.

00:48:10.280 --> 00:48:11.410
There is a right answer.

00:48:11.410 --> 00:48:12.910
But when you take
time to step back,

00:48:12.910 --> 00:48:14.615
you see it as a human activity.

00:48:14.615 --> 00:48:15.750
It's really interesting.

00:48:15.750 --> 00:48:17.480
And as a historian,
that makes work

00:48:17.480 --> 00:48:19.725
much, much more interesting
on a day-to-day basis.

00:48:19.725 --> 00:48:21.100
It's much more
interesting seeing

00:48:21.100 --> 00:48:23.780
people who came up with what
you might call a bad theory,

00:48:23.780 --> 00:48:25.250
and why they wanted
to believe that

00:48:25.250 --> 00:48:27.597
and what they got
out of it, I think.

00:48:27.597 --> 00:48:28.430
AUDIENCE: Thank you.

